<H3> <TI>   `People's Observers' Denied Access to U.S. Installations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2801195994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2801195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Gustavo Petro, M-19 [19 April Movement-Democratic 
Alliance] delegate to the Chamber of Representatives, was at the 
head of a large number of visitors to Juanchaco, where U.S. 
soldiers, whose presence is controversial, are stationed. Petro 
and his group not only could not get in but confirmed that the 
foreigners completely control the area. 
  Only four of the group of 84 were allowed into the site and 
observe everything related to the presence of U.S. troops 
stationed at Malaga Bay. The group, People's Observers, headed 
by Petro, rapidly walked around the area and confirmed that 
Colombian authorities do not control the U.S. troops. The 
Marines control everything. 
  [Begin Petro recording] The Colombian High Command does not 
control the U.S. weapons, which are locked in an 80 cubic meter 
green trailer. We also found that the Colombian military does 
not control the information dispatched from the site, which 
presently is being sent via microwave, but which later will be 
dispatched through a satellite whose ground station is being 
built. [end recording] 
  Petro said it is impossible for the People's Observers to 
operate. Not only was he not permitted to film the 
installations, but an accompanying photographer was ordered to 
stay out of the area, although he held a card authorizing entry. 

</TEXT>

