<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aristide Spokesman Issues Statement on Canadian Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2801231994 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2801231994 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The following is a press release signed by 
Jean-Claude Martineau, spokesman for President Aristide. The 
communique reads as follows: 
  A working session between the Haitian delegation, led by 
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide; and a Canadian delegation, led 
by Andre Ouellet, minister of foreign affairs, took place on 24 
January at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Ottawa. The 
session's agenda included the following points: the Haitian 
crisis; the United Nations file; the training of a managerial 
staff for a national police force, as provided for in the 
Governors Island agreement; and Haitian-Canadian bilateral 
cooperation. The two delegations agreed on the following points: 
  To disentangle the Haitian situation, the embargo must be 
total; this will shorten the duration of the crisis. 
  Other countries should be added to the four friendly 
countries that now include Canada, Venezuela, the United States, 
and France. 
  The police force can be trained outside of Haiti. It will be 
done either with the collaboration of the United States or with 
the participation of several friendly countries. This force will 
receive training not only in maintaining order and safety, but 
also in respect for the law and the Constitution. 
  The two delegations reviewed several branches of activity in 
which Haitian-Canadian cooperation will be broadened following 
the return of democracy to Haiti: education, literacy, 
cooperative communication, and energy. Also discussed was a 
radio station that would allow the Haitian people to be well 
informed about what is being done and said on their behalf 
throughout the world. This would break the rule of silence and 
disinformation imposed by the military regime. 
  This press communique is signed by Jean-Claude Martineau, 
spokesman for President Aristide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

