<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Army Commanding General Takes Office </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0102020694 Paris AFP in Spanish 2119 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0102020694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Caracas, 31 Jan (AFP) -- General Moises Orozco 
Graterol took office today as commanding general of the 
Venezuelan Army, replacing Jorge Tagliaferro de Lima after 
President-elect Rafael Caldera's decision to remove the entire 
military High Command, military sources reported. 
  General Tagliaferro de Lima is the first member of the 
military High Command to leave his post. It is expected that the 
other members, including Defense Minister Vice Admiral Radames 
Munoz will make their resignations official today or Tuesday. 
  After learning of Caldera's decision to remove them from 
their posts, the members of the High Command announced they 
would resign and request their retirement from the Armed Forces 
prior to the presidential inauguration on Wednesday. Caldera, a 
78-year-old Christian Democrat, should announce his new cabinet 
in the next few hours. Caldera will be in office from 1994 to 
1999. He had previously been president from 1969 to 1974. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

