<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Expresses `Satisfaction' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3101131194 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0524 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3101131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 31 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Despite voter 
abstentionism bordering 83 percent, Guatemalan President Ramiro 
de Leon expressed his "satisfaction" with the "yes" victory of 
today's constitutional referendum. 
  Nevertheless, in statements to the media, de Leon 
acknowledged that the "yes" victory--which garnered 84 percent 
of the votes when only 51.5 percent of the total votes have been 
tallied--did not reach the expected magnitude. 
  "In politics, what really matters, however, are final 
results," the president said, downplaying the 82.8-percent 
abstentionism evidenced by preliminary Supreme Electoral 
Tribunal [TSE] results. 
  "The Guatemalan citizen voted and represented those who 
decided not to vote," the president said. 
  The head of state attributed low voter turnout to the 
peculiarities of the referendum as well as to fears of possible 
terrorist attacks, such as ones the that occurred today and in 
the previous weeks during which dozens of bombs exploded, 
killing one, injuring 18, and causing numerous property damage, 
especially to the country's electrical system. 
  De Leon said in 60 days the reforms will become effective, 
and afterward the country's Supreme Court magistrates and 
deputies will have to resign. Last year, the president went 
through a power struggle with Supreme Court magistrates and 
deputies when he attempted to purge both institutions due to 
charges of corruption. 
  The president believes today's referendum marks a new page 
in 
the country's history, and he announced that once the 
Legislative and Judicial Branch problems were solved, he will be 
able to direct his efforts to the struggle against corruption 
and impunity. Both the Legislative and Judicial Branch will be 
changed once general elections, which have been rescheduled for 
an earlier date as contemplated in the constitutional reforms, 
takes place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32049 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat021_g_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electoral Tribunal Declares `Yes' Victory in Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3101222194 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2116 GMT 31 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3101222194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 31 Jan (NOTIMEX) -- The Supreme 
Electoral Tribunal (TSE) today confirmed victory for the "yes" 
vote in Sunday's referendum with 83.95 percent of the votes cast 
by 15.87 percent of Guatemalan voters. 
  When the count was finished in the 5,897 polling stations in 
330 municipalities, the TSE confirmed high abstentionism which 
reached 84.13 percent in the referendum on 30 [number as 
received] constitutional reforms. There were 370,044 "yes" 
votes; 70,761 "no" votes; 97,107 annulled ballots; and 7,982 
blank ballots. Of the ballots that were to be handed out to 3.4 
million Guatemalans eligible to vote, 2,890,533 were not used. 
  The results confirmed the predictions of political analysts 
about the people's indifference to the referendum, which favored 
the "yes" vote. 
  The TSE indicated that Sunday's abstentionism was the 
highest 
ever in any general election or referendum in this country, 
whose history is marked by dictatorial regimes and traditional 
electoral apathy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

