<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Threatens To Intervene </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3101225094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1548 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3101225094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 31 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Guatemalan 
President Ramiro de Leon Carpio warned today that he would 
intervene in urban freight and passenger transportation if the 
transportation sector initiates a strike tomorrow, 1 February, 
to pressure the government into approving new fares. De Leon 
said he would not allow the transportation sector to go on 
strike and that he would take legal measures, including 
intervention. 
  A truck strike could lead to a lack of fuel and losses for 
the industrial and commercial sectors, but Energy Minister Jose 
Luis Terron has guaranteed gasoline and diesel supplies. 
  Miguel Luna, president of the National Transportation 
Coordinating Board, reiterated today that the decision to stage 
a strike on Tuesday remains firm if the government does not find 
a solution to the sector's demands. Luna has not revealed the 
amount of fare increase they are demanding for cement and fuel 
transportation, but he reiterated that the decision to strike is 
firm. 

</TEXT>

