<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adherence to Strike Partial on 31 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0102182094 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0102182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 31 January, downtown Port-au-Prince's big stores 
widely adhered to the call for a 12-day strike issued by more 
than a dozen employers associations to demand that the embargo 
be lifted. The stores selling luxury goods, located mainly in 
the area between Bonne Foi and Pavee Streets, adhered to the 
strike, whereas most of the stores specializing in the sale of 
electronic parts, fabrics, and shoes conducted business as 
usual. For the informal businesses and open-air marketplaces 
too, it was business as usual; the grocery stores and banks, 
which adhered to the spirit of the movement, respected the new 
work schedule that had been set. 
  One of the nation's principal employers associations, the 
Haitian Manufacturers Association, ADIH, publicly dissociated 
itself from the Haitian Chamber of Commerce and Industry's 
movement, explaining that the movement did not have precise 
objectives -- or alternatives in case of failure. 
  In Les Cayes, Haiti's third biggest city, stores conducted 
business as usual. A Les Cayes businessman told the HAITI PRESS 
AGENCY that he was not at all involved in the events that led to 
the imposition of the strike. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-32100 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat022_b_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-022 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increasing Adherence Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0102185594 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0102185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A press release from the crisis committee and the 
presidents of the employers associations informs members and the 
general public that exchanges with national and international 
organizations, labor unions, national institutions, and the 
various sectors representative of the civilian society are 
increasing. 
  The population is increasingly adhering to the objectives 
expressed in the 25 January resolution, says the press release. 
It states, and I quote, let us continue to reinforce our 
solidarity in order to save Haiti, unquote. It should be 
pointed out that the members of the employer sector are 
reportedly to meet with the members of the union sector on 1 
February at the Haitian Chamber of Commerce and Industry. 

</TEXT>

