<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Spokesman Justifies Fuel Stockpile </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0102193894 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0102193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Over 8,000 gallons of fuel are currently stored at 
the UN/OAS mission garage in Delmas. When interviewed by Signal 
FM on 31 January, Eric Falt, the UN spokesman in Haiti, said 
this fuel is not humanitarian fuel but rather the mission's 
reserve. 
  Asked where this fuel comes from and where it is stored, 
Falt 
said the administrative and garage service controls the storage 
of such products. He explained that the UN mission does not have 
any particular facility to be supplied with fuel. Falt (?denied) 
any connection between this operation and the arrival in 
Port-au-Prince last week of approximately 30 members of the UN 
mission. This is not a redeployment of the mission in Haiti, he 
stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

