<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Transportation Strike Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   Strike Ends </H4>
<F P=102> PA0202031994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0227 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0202031994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Managua, 1 Feb (ACAN EFE) -- The Nicaraguan 
Government today announced it had reached an agreement with 
Sandinist transportation leaders to end the strike initiated 
nine days ago. The Sandinist transportation workers agreed 
tonight to end the national transportation strike "to contribute 
to the nation's stability." Presidency Minister Antonio Lacayo 
said the workers' agreement came in exchange for the 
government's willingness to negotiate in the coming days the 
demands that prompted the strike. 
  The minister agreed to hold multilateral and bilateral 
meetings with the sector's businessmen to discuss the strikers' 
demands, which include freezing fuel prices and restructuring 
the transportation sector. 
  Lacayo, President Violeta Chamorro's son-in-law, and leaders 
of the National Transportation Commission (CNT-Sandinist), 
announced the end of the strike tonight during a news conference 
at the Presidency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

