<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arnulfist Party Candidate Willing To Step Down for Possible 
Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0202014294 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0202014294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alvaro Alvarado from the "RPC Television News" </F>
newscast; passages within quotation marks are recorded] 
  [Text] Mireya Moscoso de Gruber, presidential candidate 
[for the Arnulfist Party, PA], would be willing to decline her 
candidacy in favor of a great alliance of all civilist parties 
of the country. Mireya Moscoso de Gruber thus reiterated what 
she proposed weeks ago in David when she called for a great 
alliance against the Democratic Revolutionary Party. 
  [Moscoso de Gruber] "I don't think Panamanians want to 
return to the past. We must therefore call for this great 
alliance of all parties. Let's sit down and discuss what is 
best for Panama, not what is best for personal or economic 
interests." 
  Apparently the difficulty lies in the absence of identifying 
a person to unify all these forces. 
  [Moscoso de Gruber] "Let's all sit down and look for this 
person, just as we did in 1989. 
  [Alvarado] "Even if it is not you? 
  [Moscoso de Gruber] "Even if it is not me." 
  Moscoso de Gruber said it is time to leave behind the 
arguments and political ambitions that have so harmed democracy. 
If we must hold a new convention, we are willing to hold it, 
added the leader. 
  [Moscoso de Gruber] "There are seven candidates for the 
presidency of the Republic, and we think there should be only 
two." 
  Mrs. Mireya Moscoso de Gruber made these statements during a 
meeting of the parties that form the so-called Democratic 
Alliance, alliance representatives commented later. 
  [Alfredo Arias of the PA; identified by caption] "I think 
that when we talk about a great national alliance, it has to be 
based on the alliance's majority party. 
  [Alvarado] "What do you think of a possible unification of 
criteria? 
  [Roberto Aleman of the Liberal Party; identified by caption] 
"The truth is that I do not know. Right now I think it would be 
very difficult, but it could happen. 
  [Alvarado] "Would you support it? 
  [Aleman] "I don't know. I would have to propose it to the 
party's national executive committee. 
  [Joaquin Franco of the Authentic Liberal Party; identified 
by 
caption] "I see no such possibility at this time. Mrs. Gruber 
represents the Democratic Alliance. She made some statements 
this morning, which you have already heard. We are still 
awaiting responses to those statements." 

</TEXT>

