<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Montero Takes Oath, Explains Priorities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0102194894 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0102194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A few moments ago Army Division General Rafael Angel 
Montero Revette was sworn in as defense minister. Following the 
ceremony Montero and outgoing Defense Minister Radames Munoz 
spoke with reporters. 
  [Begin recording] [Montero] I was just sworn in as defense 
minister. Yesterday and today the commanders of all the 
military forces, the Armed Forces inspector general, and the 
joint chief of staff were also sworn in, and the new military 
hierarchy will be confirmed tomorrow by President Caldera. 
  Initially I will have three priorities at the Ministry: 
social welfare; everything pertaining to sanitation, garrison 
housing, clothing, food, and so on. My second priority will be 
training; I will consider the possibility of conducting joint 
maneuvers by the entire Armed Forces during the course of the 
year. My third priority will be the maintenance and recovery of 
all the installations and equipment that may be damaged. 
  [Munoz] It is my belief -- and I would characterize this as 
a 
piece of advice to the new minister -- that it is necessary to 
consolidate the Armed Forces' spirit of democracy, support the 
country's development and, above all else, within that support 
improve the Armed Forces' efficiency in border areas to give the 
country the reassurance it needs at this time that its food 
supply will be protected. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

