<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice President Emerges `Unscathed' From Quito Demonstration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0202004294 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 1 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0202004294 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpt] Hundreds of students protested today against the 
government after fuel prices were increased by up to 71 percent. 
Despite rain and low temperatures in Quito, university and high 
school students had serious confrontations with the police, 
whose numbers have been insufficient to contain the 
demonstrators. 
  Vice President Alberto Dahik became a target of the protests 
in spite of the public force deployment downtown and throughout 
the city. A group of students threw rocks at the vice 
president's vehicle and broke the windows as he approached his 
offices near the presidential palace. Witnesses said Vice 
President Dahik emerged unscathed from the shower of rocks. The 
police reported that the demonstrators then tried to reach the 
presidential palace but were turned back by tear gas. 
  The Army began increasing security at the Ecuadoran 
presidential palace on Friday in the face of a wave of protests 
against the increase in fuel prices. More than 28 protest 
centers have been pinpointed in the capital. Students in 
Guayaquil held demonstrations during which transportation 
vehicles were hijacked and tires burned. 
  The government has announced the suspension of classes on 2, 
3, and 4 February throughout the nation in light of the general 
protest situation. Education Minister Rosalia Arteaga said: We 
ask the people to remain calm because violent attitudes do not 
solve the nation's internal problems. On the contrary, the 
problems get worse as they create a climate of uncertainty. 
Politicians responded that the Ecuadoran people have at the 
very least the right to protest. 
  Student federations and centers as well as teachers 
associations called for a strike on Wednesday. The workers 
called for a 24-hour preventive national strike on Thursday to 
protest the new prices and to exert pressure on the government 
to rectify the measures. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

