<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Earmarks Additional Funds for Chiapas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0202163894 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2045 GMT 30 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0202163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Cristobal de Las Casas, Mexico, 30 Jan 
(NOTIMEX) -- It was reported today that the Mexican Government 
has earmarked 600 million new pesos to meet the most pressing 
needs and demands of Indian and peasant communities in Chiapas 
State. 
  Alejandro Pillar Borja, delegate of the Social Development 
Secretariat in Chiapas, explained that the new resources will be 
channeled for the exclusive support of the two sectors. 
  Approached by NOTIMEX after delivering a report on 
priorities 
to Manuel Camacho Soils, commissioner for peace and 
reconciliation in Chiapas, Pillar Borja explained that the 
support does not include luxury projects. 
  On 1 January, groups of armed Indians seized four towns in 
Chiapas State in southeast Mexico, thus prompting military 
intervention and a quick conciliatory action by the government 
to restore peace. 
  In a general way, the Indians are calling for attention to 
their urgent economic, political, and social needs. 
  Pillar Borja stressed that "only the peasants and the 
Indians 
will present projects to be carried out in their places of 
origin (...) to lay the groundwork for better development in 
Chiapas." 
  The regional committees of the National Solidarity Program 
(Pronasol) will be responsible for delivering and supervising 
the funds. 
  In view of the problems caused by the conflict, Pronasol 
sped 
up its working plan to meet the most urgent demands of the poor 
people, the official explained. 

</TEXT>

