<F P=100> Paraguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wasmosy Returns Home; Will Examine U.S. Military Aid Offer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0202142794 Asuncion NOTICIAS in Spanish 2 Feb 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PY0202142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion NOTICIAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Juan Carlos Wasmosy last night said that 
he has yet to make a final decision regarding the U.S. 
Government's offer to deploy 600 U.S. servicemen in Paraguayan 
territory for five months, to erect a number of buildings in San 
Pedro Department. 
  Wasmosy denied having earlier expressed an opinion on this 
matter. He noted that all he had done so far was to meet with 
military representatives at the Armed Forces headquarters and 
with members of the Congressional Standing Committee to hear 
their views on this matter. 
  Wasmosy, who made these remarks last night upon his arrival 
in the country after visiting Ecuador and Peru, also announced 
that the Paraguayan Government will convey its decision to the 
United States through the Foreign Ministry. 
  A controvery over this issue erupted among politicians and 
lawmakers during Wasmosy's absence. Several congressmen have 
voiced support for the entry into our country of the U.S. 
servicemen. Asked whether his answer would be positive or 
negative, he said he would answer this question as soon as "I 
arrive and have time to stop and think about it." 

</TEXT>

