<H3> <TI>   PCC, UJC Report `Significant' Membership Growth in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0202163594 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1502 GMT 
2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0202163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 2 February, the newspaper GRANMA reports that the 
ranks of the Communist Party of Cuba [PCC] and the Union of 
Young Communists [UJC] experienced a significant increase in 
1993 while maintaining their selective and vanguard nature. The 
newspaper adds that approximately 50,000 people joined the PCC 
and approximately 80,000 youths joined the UJC while the 
attrition rates remained at the level of the past 15 years. The 
growth in the PCC ranks represents a important political 
process, particularly in light of the broad participation of the 
people on the outstanding workers' assemblies. [as heard] The 
PCC needs to increase its under-30 membership in order to 
include the views of the young. 

</TEXT>

