<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Executive To Establish Data Base To Fight Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0202192594 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0202192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] (Sonia Ciambatti), former magistrate of the Supreme 
Court of Justice, said that the Executive Branch, through the 
Central Bank of Venezuela, will begin operating a data base that 
will allow the detection and neutralization of money transfers 
linked to drug-trafficking activities that are coming into the 
country from overseas. (Ciambatti) made the announcement within 
the framework of a conference in Caracas on U.S. experiences in 
fighting money laundering in the United States. 
  If money laundering is not eradicated, it is capable of 
spilling over and harming the financial system of a nation, 
because people involved in money laundering take advantage of 
the system for their own benefit. According to (Ciambatti), 
Venezuela has acquired international tools, such as the Vienna 
Convention and the standard regulations on the legitimization of 
capital, that enable a country to fight the crime. Establishing 
the proposed data base, therefore, will be a smooth process. 
  [Begin (Ciambatti) recording, in progress] ... so there is a 
check to allow only banking transfers and economic situations 
that are entirely legal and which benefit the country and to 
keep Venezuela from becoming a center of operations for 
international drug-trafficking activities. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

