<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gilles Claims Embargo Has Multiplied Misery </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0202233194 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1700 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0202233194 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The leader of PANPRA [National, Progressive 
Revolutionary Party of Haiti] Serge Gilles reiterated his 
opposition to the worsening of the sanctions against Haiti. 
  Serge Gilles today expressed opposition to the sanctions on 
Haiti in the form of a total embargo, said that he considered it 
an erroneous approach by the international community that will 
only aggravate the sufferings of the people. In a statement to 
the Agence France-Presse, Gilles pointed out that based on what 
he saw within the country, the suffering of the people was 
increasing dramatically. 
  The embargo did not create the structural misery in Haiti, 
he 
said, but it has multiplied this misery six or seven times. The 
increase in the rate of child mortality and the destruction of 
production capacity are palpable facts, Serge Gilles pointed 
out, adding that those who are motivated by those sanctions are 
doing well at the expense of the people. Mr. Gilles advocated 
the search for a consensus through a national conference, 
excluding no one, with a view toward forming first a government 
of national concord. 
  It should be recalled, according to some independent 
humanitarian religious sources, that the embargo against Haiti, 
imposed in October 1991, has caused the deaths of more than 
10,000 people in vulnerable groups, mostly children and the 
elderly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

